PROGRESS.txt

    Note: To ensure easy tracking, all project progress, updates, and milestones will be documented in this file along with their respective dates.

Update: April 22, 2026

Completed Tasks:

  The general Input/Output (I/O) loop of the CLI application has been successfully implemented.

  Class and module architecture is being strictly maintained in accordance with SOLID principles and Clean Architecture.

  Fully Implemented Commands: pwd, rm, rn, exit, help.
  
  Halfly Implemented Commands: ls, cd

Incomplete Commands:

  cp (Copy)

  mv (Move)

Backlog / Missing Features:

  ls Command: Missing execution flags (e.g., -l, -a).

  cd Command: Missing path resolution shortcuts such as current directory (.) and parent directory (..).

  Session Management: Clipboard functionality and Command History are not yet implemented.

  UI Enhancements: An advanced console library has not yet been integrated.

  Audit Trail: Action and error logging mechanism is missing.

  Core Logic: Both Command-layer wrappers and Core-layer NIO.2 implementations for the cp and mv operations are currently pending.

  Advanced Features: Archiving, encryption, and compression algorithms are not yet introduced to the system.

  Documentation: The ui module and core module implementations lack proper Javadoc documentation. (Note: Most API modules have been thoroughly documented).

Progress Guidelines (Rules of Engagement):

  Strict SOLID Adherence: Future development must continue to follow SOLID principles.

  Loose Coupling: Extreme care must be taken to ensure module independence is not violated (e.g., UI should not leak into Core).

  Testing (Addition): As core operations become more complex, writing Unit Tests for crucial components (like parsers and path resolvers) should be considered.

Architectural Thoughts & Future Planning:

  Encryption Architecture: Encryption algorithms could be implemented as static methods within utility classes in a util module. (Architectural Note: If multiple algorithms like AES and RSA will be used, adopting the Strategy Pattern via an EncryptionStrategy interface might be a more SOLID approach than static utilities).

  Console Library: Lanterna is being considered as the primary text-based UI library. To prevent cluttering the main program loop, this library will be abstracted behind a dedicated UI class (e.g., ConsoleRenderer). Once this integration is stable, the entire ui module must be fully documented.

